SIMPLE: stale
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stale
<hw>Stale</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stale</ets>, <ets>stele</ets>, AS. <ets>stael</ets>,
<ets>stel</ets>; akin to LG. & D. <ets>steel</ets>, G. <ets>stiel</ets>;
cf. L. <ets>stilus</ets> stake, stalk, stem, Gr. <grk>steleo`n</grk> a
handle, and E. <ets>stall</ets>, <ets>stalk</ets>, n.]</ety> <def>The
stock or handle of anything; <as>as, the <ex>stale</ex> of a
rake</as>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>steal</asp>,
<asp>stele</asp>, etc.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But seeing the arrow's <qex>stale</qex> without, and that the head
did go⟦br⟧
No further than it might be seen.</q> <rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stale
<hw>Stale</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Akin to <ets>stale</ets> urine, and
to <ets>stall</ets>, n.; probably from Low German or Scandinavian. Cf.
<er>Stale</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Vapid or
tasteless from age; having lost its life, spirit, and flavor, from being
long kept; <as>as, <ex>stale</ex> beer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not new; not freshly made; <as>as, <ex>stale</ex>
bread</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having lost the life or graces of youth; worn out;
decayed.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>stale</xex> virgin.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Worn out by use or familiarity; having lost its
novelty and power of pleasing; trite; common.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wit itself, if <qex>stale</qex> is less pleasing.</q>
<rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How weary, <qex>stale</qex> flat, and unprofitable⟦br⟧
Seem to me all the uses of this world!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stale affidavit</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>an
affidavit held above a year.</cd> <au>Craig.</au> -- <col><b>Stale
demand</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a claim or demand which has not
been pressed or demanded for a long time.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stale
<hw>Stale</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Staled</conjf> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Staling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make vapid or tasteless; to
destroy the life, beauty, or use of; to wear out.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Age can not wither her, nor custom <qex>stale</qex>⟦br⟧
Her infinite variety.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stale
<hw>Stale</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Akin to D. & G.
<ets>stallen</ets>, Dan. <ets>stalle</ets>, Sw. <ets>stalla</ets>, and
E. <ets>stall</ets> a stable. ⟦root⟧ 163. See <er>Stall</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Stale</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To make
water; to discharge urine; -- said especially of horses and
cattle.</def> <rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Stale
<hw>Stale</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Stale</er>, <pos>a.</pos> &
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is stale or worn out
by long keeping, or by use.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A prostitute.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Urine, esp. that of beasts.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Stale</xex> of horses.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Stale
<hw>Stale</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>estal</ets> place,
position, abode, market, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧tal</ets> a butcher's stall,
OHG. <ets>stal</ets> station, place, stable, G. <ets>stall</ets> (see
<er>Stall</er>, <pos>n.</pos>); or from OE. <ets>stale</ets> theft, AS.
<ets>stalu</ets> (see <er>Steal</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>).]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Something set, or offered to view, as an allurement to
draw others to any place or purpose; a decoy; a stool pigeon.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Still, as he went, he crafty <qex>stales</qex> did lay.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stalking-horse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>B. Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chess)</fld> <def>A stalemate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A laughingstock; a dupe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stalely</ent>⟦br⟧
